35
00:02:03.780 --> 00:02:07.340
So a bit more about the multi-kingdom microbial determinants of cancer.

36
00:02:08.340 --> 00:02:11.600
The gut microbiome literature thus far has been largely dominated by bacteria.

37
00:02:11.660 --> 00:02:12.700
That makes a ton of sense.

38
00:02:13.980 --> 00:02:17.380
But that's not all that's there. The gut harbors a rather rich

39
00:02:17.620 --> 00:02:21.120
ecosystem that includes fungi, protozoa, archaea, and

40
00:02:21.180 --> 00:02:24.940
viruses, and you'll hear us talk a little bit about each of those

41
00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:28.640
kingdoms in some detail. And collectively, they constitute a

42
00:02:28.660 --> 00:02:31.600
substantial fraction of the gut microbiome's

43
00:02:31.680 --> 00:02:35.640
biomass, and encoded genetic diversity, as well as the metabolites that

44
00:02:35.680 --> 00:02:38.600
might be responsible for the downstream biology that we observe.

45
00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:43.160
Non-bacterial organisms modulate host immunity, metabolism,

46
00:02:43.480 --> 00:02:46.620
and cancer susceptibility, but remain systematically understudied.

47
00:02:47.860 --> 00:02:51.340
An important point here is that the gut microbiome and its comparatively high

48
00:02:51.460 --> 00:02:55.329
microbial biomass is not necessarily the same as the intra-tumoral microbiome,

49
00:02:55.380 --> 00:02:57.800
which is comparatively lower biomass.

50
00:02:58.300 --> 00:03:02.120
They represent distinct compartments with distinct biology, and so we'll always

51
00:03:02.160 --> 00:03:05.000
try to clarify what particular compartment we're

52
00:03:05.020 --> 00:03:08.799
discussing. And this field is nicely framed by a

53
00:03:08.840 --> 00:03:11.200
couple of laudatory recent reviews.

54
00:03:12.640 --> 00:03:16.450
One of which was co-authored by one of our esteemed colleagues and

55
00:03:16.560 --> 00:03:20.300
speakers here, Dr. Iliev, as well as a review in JAMA that came

56
00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:21.500
out sometime last year.

57
00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:27.660
So we use this timeline from the aforementioned review

58
00:03:27.700 --> 00:03:29.310
that came out last year

59
00:03:30.600 --> 00:03:31.190
to

60
00:03:32.180 --> 00:03:35.680
offer a little bit of context for how high-throughput sequencing and the

61
00:03:35.720 --> 00:03:38.080
culture-independent microbiome have really exploded.

62
00:03:38.940 --> 00:03:42.800
Going back to 1911, we're not going to start from the very beginning, but we

63
00:03:42.840 --> 00:03:46.680
have the demonstration that chicken sarcoma is transmissible by a retrovirus.

64
00:03:47.220 --> 00:03:50.920
Consequently, we have the onset of what is being colloquially called the

65
00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:54.880
genomics era in the early 2010s, where both Fusobacterium and

66
00:03:54.960 --> 00:03:58.260
ptx positive E. coli were subsequently linked to colorectal cancer

67
00:03:58.740 --> 00:03:59.840
incidence and severity.

68
00:04:00.740 --> 00:04:04.580
And then more recent findings include Strep anginosus being shown to promote

69
00:04:04.620 --> 00:04:06.620
gastric cancer in experimental models.

70
00:04:07.260 --> 00:04:11.240
All this to say that the explosion of high-throughput sequencing

71
00:04:11.300 --> 00:04:14.280
have really allowed us to do a much better job of

72
00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:18.079
discovering not only who's there, but what are they doing.

73
00:04:20.640 --> 00:04:23.400
So the first part of my talk is called Blastocystis: Friend or Foe?

74
00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:28.840
Here we can see that the Mayo Clinic describes Blastocystis as a

75
00:04:28.900 --> 00:04:32.640
microscopic parasite that can live in your digestive tract.

76
00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:36.380
Researchers don't fully understand the role that Blastocystis plays, if

77
00:04:36.600 --> 00:04:38.140
any, in causing disease.

78
00:04:39.240 --> 00:04:43.060
Most commonly, Blastocystis organisms simply live in a person's digestive tract

79
00:04:43.080 --> 00:04:46.000
without causing harm. And so it's this sort of,

80
00:04:46.840 --> 00:04:49.770
not only notoriety, but indecision about what it actually does.

81
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:52.060
Is it actually a parasite? Is it a commensal?

82
00:04:52.140 --> 00:04:54.050
You kind of see it described as both.

83
00:04:54.050 --> 00:04:56.960
That makes this particular organism very interesting scientifically.

84
00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:02.200
So Blastocystis, formerly Blastocystis hominis, which

85
00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:04.460
you might have heard it referred to

86
00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:09.560
by its prior name. It's a bit of a misnomer because it turns

87
00:05:09.660 --> 00:05:13.000
out this particular organism is commonly found in the human gut,

88
00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:15.820
but also other animals. So not just H**o sapiens.

89
00:05:16.360 --> 00:05:18.960
It's categorized into genetically distinct subtypes,

90
00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:23.920
at least eight of which seem to have tropism for the human gut, although there's

91
00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:26.880
probably more we just lack from high-quality draft genomes.

92
00:05:27.520 --> 00:05:31.280
Like I mentioned, it has a controversial clinical and ecological role, and

93
00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:35.280
it's notoriously recalcitrant to growth in anything but the

94
00:05:35.320 --> 00:05:37.040
simplest experimental communities.

95
00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:40.700
But it can be detected pretty reliably with PCR and metagenomics.

96
00:05:42.100 --> 00:05:43.900
So to boil down our work, we

97
00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:49.060
performed a population-scale interrogation of gut microbiome among participants in

98
00:05:49.100 --> 00:05:51.520
the ZOE PREDICT studies. A little bit more on that in a moment.

99
00:05:51.960 --> 00:05:55.640
This was complemented by newly sequenced data from various privileged datasets that

100
00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:58.940
we had access to, as well as publicly available data, all told

101
00:05:59.500 --> 00:06:01.800
collectively comprising more than 50,000 individuals.

102
00:06:02.300 --> 00:06:05.870
Consequently, to perform this study, we had to generate a customized computational

103
00:06:05.940 --> 00:06:09.150
workflow to describe the landscape across 214 different hosts,

104
00:06:09.640 --> 00:06:13.500
lifespan, and eras, where we described Blastocystis prevalence,

105
00:06:13.600 --> 00:06:17.160
abundance, and subtype distribution, and subsequently found

106
00:06:17.700 --> 00:06:21.620
pretty compelling links to diet, cardiometabolic biomarkers, body adiposity,

107
00:06:21.760 --> 00:06:25.662
and diseases.So, as promised, a little bit

108
00:06:25.672 --> 00:06:27.042
more about the ZOE PREDICT studies.

109
00:06:27.952 --> 00:06:30.622
They comprise at least five different cohorts,

110
00:06:31.732 --> 00:06:35.532
collectively one of the largest multi-omic population health initiatives linking

111
00:06:35.592 --> 00:06:38.912
nutrition, individualized metabolic responses to food, and the gut

112
00:06:38.952 --> 00:06:40.692
microbiome. At last check,

113
00:06:42.432 --> 00:06:43.082
this

114
00:06:44.172 --> 00:06:48.152
program has now enrolled nearly 400,000 individuals across three

115
00:06:48.192 --> 00:06:48.852
different countries.

116
00:06:51.552 --> 00:06:54.592
So for this particular study that I'm going to be describing, we jointly considered

117
00:06:54.612 --> 00:06:56.392
and harmonized five different PREDICT studies.

118
00:06:56.421 --> 00:06:57.272
There's PREDICT 1,

119
00:06:58.272 --> 00:07:01.832
where we admitted over 1,000 individuals to

120
00:07:01.892 --> 00:07:04.392
metabolic research kitchens and did all the omics.

121
00:07:05.192 --> 00:07:08.912
PREDICT 2, where we ran back the same playbook in largely remote fashion.

122
00:07:09.432 --> 00:07:11.872
And then various forms of the PREDICT 3 study,

123
00:07:12.712 --> 00:07:15.652
which are largely paying customers of a precision nutrition app.

124
00:07:18.112 --> 00:07:18.852
So here in this map,

125
00:07:20.672 --> 00:07:23.612
we demonstrate that blastocystis is widely prevalent globally.

126
00:07:23.672 --> 00:07:26.832
If you know anything about blastocystis epidemiology, this isn't going to blow your

127
