00:16:31.188 --> 00:16:34.748
MASLD versus control, and we can find that off-diagonal, which is where

280
00:16:35.148 --> 00:16:36.928
the beta coefficients don't necessarily agree.

281
00:16:37.788 --> 00:16:40.488
We find pretty interesting biology and an enrichment of

282
00:16:40.548 --> 00:16:43.928
pro-inflammatory oral microbes, especially in non-lean

283
00:16:43.988 --> 00:16:45.788
MASLD.

284
00:16:47.868 --> 00:16:51.368
This was a pretty interesting result, where we were able to demonstrate that

285
00:16:51.408 --> 00:16:54.308
acylcarnitine is the largest class of enriched compounds in MASLD.

286
00:16:55.048 --> 00:16:57.438
As their chain length increased,

287
00:16:59.168 --> 00:17:02.568
there was a stark association with the microbes that we

288
00:17:02.608 --> 00:17:06.288
linked to MASLD. Again, it doesn't lend itself well

289
00:17:06.368 --> 00:17:09.449
to this particular presentation, but depicted here in the rows,

290
00:17:10.449 --> 00:17:14.368
we have the differentially abundant bacteria as well as the

291
00:17:14.429 --> 00:17:17.648
acylcarnitines that were sorted by chain length, and you can see this really

292
00:17:17.689 --> 00:17:20.878
striking block structure that coincides

293
00:17:21.429 --> 00:17:23.648
with diet quality and their association.

294
00:17:24.098 --> 00:17:26.528
And so we found a very interesting

295
00:17:27.248 --> 00:17:28.708
diet-by-metabolite

296
00:17:29.848 --> 00:17:31.948
relationship that's mediated by the microbiome.

297
00:17:34.868 --> 00:17:35.708
What about viruses?

298
00:17:36.828 --> 00:17:40.378
In terms of agnostic high-throughput viral profiling, most

299
00:17:40.428 --> 00:17:44.178
taxonomic profilers, which tell you which bugs are there, they ignore viruses

300
00:17:44.178 --> 00:17:47.848
completely. They require de novo assembly, or they rely on pretty

301
00:17:47.908 --> 00:17:51.228
unstable reference taxonomies. That's because viruses lack

302
00:17:51.908 --> 00:17:54.708
universal marker genes. They evolve and mutate rapidly.

303
00:17:54.748 --> 00:17:57.418
They share homology with our genes, with bacterial genes.

304
00:17:57.908 --> 00:18:01.688
So taxonomy is particularly brittle across databases and releases.

305
00:18:02.228 --> 00:18:06.188
So we tagged in a very talented PhD student named Jordan Jensen,

306
00:18:06.268 --> 00:18:10.028
who will be joining my group for a postdoctoral fellowship, presuming a successful

307
00:18:10.068 --> 00:18:10.828
defense this week.

308
00:18:11.708 --> 00:18:13.728
Her clever take on this is to

309
00:18:16.908 --> 00:18:20.738
generate 100 base pair marker regions as opposed to marker genes

310
00:18:20.788 --> 00:18:24.458
to specifically identify which viruses are present,

311
00:18:24.868 --> 00:18:28.288
and all of this is without the upstream wet lab viral

312
00:18:28.328 --> 00:18:31.128
purification protocols that might otherwise be

313
00:18:31.168 --> 00:18:34.548
required. And so this method, which we call

314
00:18:34.688 --> 00:18:38.678
Baklava, the preprint is out, the repo is public, and

315
00:18:38.708 --> 00:18:42.048
we think it represents a better mousetrap in terms of telling you which

316
00:18:42.068 --> 00:18:43.717
viruses are in your particular

317
00:18:43.728 --> 00:18:47.592
sample.And here we can

318
00:18:47.652 --> 00:18:51.112
see that endogenous viruses distinguish MASLD and its subtype.

319
00:18:51.912 --> 00:18:55.432
The very interesting result here is that the majority of them are so-called

320
00:18:55.472 --> 00:18:58.292
unclassified or uncultivated viruses.

321
00:18:58.552 --> 00:19:02.312
That is, they don't have a name, but we can reliably detect them.

322
00:19:02.772 --> 00:19:06.752
This is offering us a lot of future directions in terms of

323
00:19:06.812 --> 00:19:09.192
uncovering this so-called viral dark matter.

324
00:19:09.872 --> 00:19:13.502
The one significantly altered virus that does have known taxonomy is

325
00:19:13.532 --> 00:19:14.932
Punavirus P1,

326
00:19:15.972 --> 00:19:18.992
which has never been studied in the context of MASLD but has been associated with

327
00:19:19.032 --> 00:19:20.612
other pro-inflammatory disorders.

328
00:19:23.252 --> 00:19:26.792
When we do a bit of genome gazing in terms of

329
00:19:27.212 --> 00:19:30.932
what viruses are differentially abundant by subtype, we did notice

330
00:19:31.012 --> 00:19:31.342
that

331
00:19:32.932 --> 00:19:36.312
the viruses in MASLD versus controls, and especially lean MASLD--

332
00:19:37.272 --> 00:19:41.082
Excuse me, that should say non-lean MASLD, consisted of generally larger genomes,

333
00:19:41.352 --> 00:19:45.212
greater GC content, and a greater number of open reading frames, really suggesting

334
00:19:45.232 --> 00:19:49.212
that in non-lean MASLD, you have these viral taxa that could be more

335
00:19:49.272 --> 00:19:49.831
complex.

336
00:19:51.232 --> 00:19:54.742
And then this was a very interesting result for us where we used a computational

337
00:19:54.772 --> 00:19:57.532
workflow to predict

338
00:19:58.712 --> 00:20:02.392
phage-host pairs. And what we were able to demonstrate is that

339
00:20:03.392 --> 00:20:06.312
the viruses that were differentially abundant

340
00:20:07.432 --> 00:20:08.192
in MASLD

341
00:20:09.632 --> 00:20:12.712
were predicted to infect and kill their

342
00:20:13.752 --> 00:20:14.652
bacterial host,

343
00:20:15.712 --> 00:20:17.552
especially those that were differentially abundant.

344
00:20:17.612 --> 00:20:21.212
So this to us really indicated bona fide predator-prey

345
00:20:21.272 --> 00:20:21.892
dynamics,

346
00:20:23.092 --> 00:20:26.932
where the enrichment or depletion of viruses that kill

347
00:20:27.012 --> 00:20:30.832
bacteria could be responsible for some of the alterations in gut bacteria that we

348
00:20:30.892 --> 00:20:31.652
see in this disease.

349
00:20:34.112 --> 00:20:36.232
So we'll be a bit brief here as our time's running short.

350
00:20:37.052 --> 00:20:40.652
But in summary, we performed high-resolution profiling in more than 700

351
00:20:40.692 --> 00:20:41.412
individuals.

352
00:20:42.552 --> 00:20:46.172
We show this oral typical microbe axis, and

353
00:20:46.772 --> 00:20:49.652
what's most exciting is we provided this as a comprehensive resource without

354
00:20:49.692 --> 00:20:50.912
controlled access. So if you

355
00:20:51.852 --> 00:20:55.491
make your way to our data availability page, all of this data is free for you to

356
00:20:55.592 --> 00:20:55.832
use

357
00:20:57.272 --> 00:20:58.412
without signing up for anything.

358
00:21:00.352 --> 00:21:04.142
Where to read more. We have more on host genetics, trans-kingdom interactions,

359
00:21:05.512 --> 00:21:06.972
subtype persistence, and we even

360
00:21:08.092 --> 00:21:11.992
profiled ancient paleofeces to show that blastocystis

361
00:21:12.012 --> 00:21:15.392
is not just a sign of a modern gut microbial configuration.

362
00:21:15.792 --> 00:21:19.312
So this was published last year, as was Hansel's paper.

363
00:21:22.452 --> 00:21:26.392
In terms of ongoing work, now that we've built a better mousetrap, we think, in

364
00:21:26.452 --> 00:21:26.952
terms of

365
00:21:28.252 --> 00:21:30.492
generating viral profiles from gut metagenomes.

366
00:21:31.112 --> 00:21:33.972
We went back to a cohort that we'd previously published on

367
00:21:34.872 --> 00:21:38.852
in Lynch Syndrome, showing a distinct microbiome signature in Lynch--

368
00:21:39.332 --> 00:21:43.072
viral signature in Lynch syndrome compared to precancerous polyps

369
00:21:43.132 --> 00:21:44.452
compared to colorectal cancer.

370
00:21:45.332 --> 00:21:47.462
This paper is currently in submission,

371
00:21:48.532 --> 00:21:52.352
but we have found the work to be promising enough to want to

372
00:21:52.392 --> 00:21:56.272
extend on its findings with a large consortium with many

373
00:21:56.312 --> 00:21:57.992
collaborators who I'm sure you're familiar with.

374
00:22:00.072 --> 00:22:00.412
Next,

375
00:22:01.872 --> 00:22:05.572
one troubling

376
00:22:05.672 --> 00:22:09.552
issue with current-day metabolomics studies is that

377
00:22:09.592 --> 00:22:13.471
less than 1% of what we find has a mass spec

378
00:22:13.552 --> 00:22:15.742
standard, meaning we actually know what it is.

379
00:22:15.752 --> 00:22:19.612
And so we've got a computational workflow to sort of de-orphan these bioactive

380
00:22:19.672 --> 00:22:20.632
metabolites, finding

381
00:22:22.332 --> 00:22:26.292
differential associations between MASLD and controls, and especially in HCC,

382
00:22:27.572 --> 00:22:29.972
suggesting that these metabolites may be

383
00:22:30.012 --> 00:22:33.412
microbially modified. And so we have

384
00:22:33.692 --> 00:22:36.952
experimental colleagues who are following up on some orthogonal leads that we've

385
00:22:36.962 --> 00:22:40.052
generated. And of course, this will be the topic of Dr.

386
00:22:40.292 --> 00:22:44.092
Kim's KO1 since she opened up her own lab at MD

387
00:22:44.132 --> 00:22:44.632
Anderson.

388
00:22:45.832 --> 00:22:46.712
And then finally,

389
00:22:47.612 --> 00:22:51.582
we are generating a network-based framework to detect enzymes

390
00:22:51.592 --> 00:22:55.152
that catalyze reactions of interest and microbial derivatives of

391
00:22:55.192 --> 00:22:56.432
well-characterized metabolites.

392
00:22:58.252 --> 00:23:00.012
So with that, those are my acknowledgments.

393
00:23:01.252 --> 00:23:04.712
And if it's okay with the group, we'll just proceed to the next speaker, and then

394
00:23:04.732 --> 00:23:05.872
we'll take Q&amp;A all at once.

395
00:23:06.992 --> 00:23:10.292
So it's my pleasure to introduce Dr. Caleb La Roe.

396
00:23:27.152 --> 00:23:31.072
You for being here. I'll be talking today mostly about the virome and

397
00:23:31.152 --> 00:23:33.592
specifically talking on Epstein-Barr virus.

398
00:23:34.992 --> 00:23:38.222
So before getting into the scientific bit of the talk, I just want to briefly

399
00:23:38.232 --> 00:23:40.552
introduce the group and the folks that actually did the work.

400
00:23:41.492 --> 00:23:45.292
So I started my group in September of 2023 at Sloan Kettering,

401
00:23:45.472 --> 00:23:49.352
and I like to think that we are a technology development lab that has increasingly

402
00:23:49.392 --> 00:23:51.672
found really cool associations with viruses.

403
00:23:51.701 --> 00:23:55.212
And so this has been something that has really been the focal point of the biology

404
00:23:55.232 --> 00:23:58.712
in our group. And so today I'll be telling you really about a single story that was

405
00:23:58.752 --> 00:24:02.412
led by Sherry and Aaron that are trainees in the group in a close collaboration

406
00:24:02.452 --> 00:24:06.292
with Ryan, who is another fellow junior PI at Baylor

407
00:24:06.372 --> 00:24:09.936
College of Medicine.So like many of you,

408
00:24:10.056 --> 00:24:13.676
in 2020, the world changed the way that I think about science

409
00:24:13.776 --> 00:24:17.466
dramatically, in that we had a new infectious agent that was

410
00:24:17.476 --> 00:24:21.376
causing a global havoc, and it really sort of gave me pause to evaluate what

411
00:24:21.396 --> 00:24:25.356
it meant to sort of coexist as a human with these infectious agents in

412
00:24:25.376 --> 00:24:28.616
our society. And as I started to dig into this concept,

413
00:24:29.256 --> 00:24:33.196
something that really blew me away was just how abundant viral particles are

414
00:24:33.256 --> 00:24:36.376
on the human body, irrespective of an actual infectious state.

415
00:24:36.876 --> 00:24:40.276
So there's this concept now of the human virome, which is the

416
00:24:40.516 --> 00:24:44.436
constellation of about 380 trillion viral particles

417
00:24:44.476 --> 00:24:46.576
that are coexisting on your body right now.

418
00:24:47.096 --> 00:24:50.976
And so what that means is for every estimated human cell on your body, there are

419
00:24:51.076 --> 00:24:54.756
about 10 viral particles. So many of these are phages, but many of these are also

420
00:24:54.796 --> 00:24:58.686
eukaryotic viruses that are essentially constantly shaping the way

421
00:24:58.736 --> 00:25:02.706
that our cells and our immune system is responding to any sort of

422
00:25:02.716 --> 00:25:04.636
perturbation that we have in our body.

423
00:25:04.785 --> 00:25:08.636
And so it's really this concept of a virome that is sort of fundamentally

424
00:25:08.676 --> 00:25:10.756
changing the way that I think about the science that I do.

425
00:25:11.716 --> 00:25:13.486
What I'm specifically interested in is

426
00:25:14.356 --> 00:25:17.416
sort of contrary to the way that we've conventionally gone about virology, where we

427
00:25:17.516 --> 00:25:20.416
see acute symptoms, we see someone with a fever or a rash.

428
00:25:21.276 --> 00:25:25.216
The fact that some of these viral infections can actually cause chronic long-term

429
00:25:25.256 --> 00:25:29.166
complications, but ultimately, since they don't manifest in,

430
00:25:29.236 --> 00:25:32.476
say, the same acute pathology, these have gone understudied to date.

431
00:25:33.136 --> 00:25:36.866
And so what I want to leave you with in this talk or what I hope you'll take away

432
00:25:36.896 --> 00:25:40.396
from this, is that just due to the sheer abundance of viral

433
00:25:40.436 --> 00:25:44.236
particles in and on our bodies, every time you do a DNA sequencing

434
00:25:44.276 --> 00:25:47.676
experiment from human cells, you will be capturing viral nucleic

435
00:25:47.736 --> 00:25:50.856
acids. And as a function of that, you can do some really insightful

436
00:25:50.876 --> 00:25:54.856
biology just by kind of systematically reanalyzing your data

437
00:25:54.876 --> 00:25:58.806
in a capacity that allows for new insights from these viral particles.

438
00:25:58.916 --> 00:26:01.736
And that's exactly the approach that we took in this study, and I'll give you a

439
00:26:02.116 --> 00:26:03.296
specific vignette on this.

440
00:26:04.536 --> 00:26:08.356
So whenever I think about how chronic impacts of viral infections can be

441
00:26:08.416 --> 00:26:12.316
very heterogeneous and how they're sort of non-intuitive in terms of

442
00:26:12.416 --> 00:26:16.236
their long-term complications versus their acute pathologies, really, I think

443
00:26:16.276 --> 00:26:18.996
Epstein-Barr virus is the poster child for this phenomenon.

444
00:26:19.696 --> 00:26:23.516
So Epstein-Barr virus is a gamma herpes virus. It has a fairly large genome.

445
00:26:23.556 --> 00:26:27.376
It's about 172 KB, and it establishes tropism in B

446
00:26:27.396 --> 00:26:31.126
cells. But what's really fascinating about EBV is about

447
00:26:31.136 --> 00:26:34.706
probably 95% of us, or probably all of us in this room, have actually been

448
00:26:34.736 --> 00:26:38.605
infected by this virus. And so if you think about what

449
00:26:38.636 --> 00:26:40.396
follows this acute infection,

450
00:26:41.376 --> 00:26:45.206
there are a wide-ranging set of consequences that

451
00:26:45.236 --> 00:26:48.816
ultimately follow. So it's now been definitively shown that multiple

452
00:26:48.836 --> 00:26:52.676
sclerosis is a long-term manifestation of an Epstein-Barr virus

453
00:26:52.716 --> 00:26:56.076
that can be acquired typically decades prior to disease onset.

454
00:26:56.836 --> 00:27:00.336
In certain parts of the world, EBV is a common driver of nasopharyngeal

455
00:27:00.376 --> 00:27:04.096
carcinoma, again, indicating that this virus does have oncogenic

456
00:27:04.136 --> 00:27:07.876
potential in and of itself. But for most of us in this room, again, we've been

457
00:27:07.916 --> 00:27:11.336
infected, but we had no sort of obvious acute symptoms.

458
00:27:11.376 --> 00:27:14.756
You would develop mononucleosis, but typically this is controlled.

459
00:27:15.376 --> 00:27:18.896
But fortunately, most of us do not have these long-term complications that can be

460
00:27:18.956 --> 00:27:22.776
quite debilitating. And so the question that we've been obsessed with for quite

461
00:27:22.816 --> 00:27:26.316
some time now is really trying to understand why is it that people are

462
00:27:26.356 --> 00:27:29.756
responding so variable to the same infectious agent?

463
00:27:30.156 --> 00:27:33.156
And ultimately, could we try to understand this variation in a way that we could

464
00:27:33.196 --> 00:27:35.836
actually sort of predict and potentially intervene?

465
00:27:36.396 --> 00:27:39.676
And our main hypothesis in this study and the way that we've kind of conducted

466
00:27:39.696 --> 00:27:43.516
these large-scale analyses is ultimately anticipating that the genetic

467
00:27:43.536 --> 00:27:47.186
variation in all of us as humans actually is underlying this

468
00:27:47.216 --> 00:27:50.716
significant phenotypic response to this infectious agent.

469
00:27:50.736 --> 00:27:54.476
And so we essentially try to build a platform to be able to understand how host

470
00:27:54.516 --> 00:27:58.246
genetic variation could ultimately modulate the way that EBV infects and leads to

471
00:27:58.296 --> 00:28:01.136
these variable long-term infection consequences.

472
00:28:02.456 --> 00:28:06.436
So the key concept that we take advantage of in this approach is leveraging

473
00:28:06.456 --> 00:28:10.356
the fact that as a herpes virus, EBV will leave a copy of its genome in

474
00:28:10.436 --> 00:28:14.206
cells. So if you think about sort of a simplified model of viral infection,

475
00:28:15.116 --> 00:28:17.836
cells in our body are going to be hit by this viral agent.

476
00:28:18.296 --> 00:28:22.106
Some of them will actually become vectors for this virus to replicate

477
00:28:22.136 --> 00:28:25.716
itself in. And fortunately, our immune system is going to kick in and clear these

478
00:28:25.756 --> 00:28:28.596
infected cells relatively effectively.

479
00:28:28.616 --> 00:28:32.066
But again, this key feature of herpes viruses in particular is that they'll

480
00:28:32.116 --> 00:28:36.046
actually leave a copy of their genome in a subset of these cells, and this is a

481
00:28:36.056 --> 00:28:39.766
phenomenon called latency. And so what herpes viruses do, will take advantage of

482
00:28:39.796 --> 00:28:42.906
this latency to potentially then reactivate and have a secondary infection,

483
00:28:42.976 --> 00:28:46.416
sometimes decades later. And so if you sort of

484
00:28:46.496 --> 00:28:50.356
realize that there's a copy of these genetic materials sort of

